## Key Findings (scope, axes, posture)

1. **Inspect AI + inspect_evals provide all five tasks.** SWE-Bench (`inspect_evals/swe_bench` and `_verified_mini`), WMDP (`wmdp_bio`, `wmdp_chem`, `wmdp_cyber`), AgentHarm (`agentharm`, `agentharm_benign` with `n_irrelevant_tools` as a first-class param), TruthfulQA (`truthfulqa`), and either MT-Bench / Arena-Hard via the registry or — verify on install — via a thin local wrapper task pulling FastChat / arena-hard-auto datasets. Pinned: `inspect-ai==0.3.224` (May 20 2026), `inspect-evals==0.5.2` (Mar 19 2026), `inspect-scout==0.4.28` (Meridian Labs).
2. **Scaffold variance dominates model variance on SWE-Bench Verified.** Morph LLC's 2026 leaderboard analysis writes verbatim: "The same model (Opus 4.5) scores 45.9% with standardized scaffolding and 51.8% with Auggie's scaffolding"; this number is confirmed by Augment Code's own blog: "Auggie CLI takes the top spot on SWE-bench Pro, solving 51.80% of real-world software engineering tasks. For reference, Scale's own leaderboard shows Claude Opus 4.5 hitting 45.89% when run through SWE-Agent." On SWE-Bench Pro, particula.tech reports a "22-point performance swing from scaffold changes alone." OpenAI's 2026 audit (per morphllm.com) found "every frontier model tested—including GPT-5.2, Claude Opus 4.5, and Gemini 3 Flash—could reproduce verbatim gold patches or problem statement specifics for certain SWE-bench Verified tasks. They also found that 59.4% of the hardest unsolved problems had flawed test cases." Treat Verified scores with the explicit contamination caveat.
3. **WMDP is load-bearing and untested for perturbation sensitivity.** 1273 Bio + 408 Chem MCQ items (1681 total in v2 scope; Cyber's 1987 items deferred), simple-accuracy scoring, default Inspect prompt is the canonical letter-only format. NIST CAISI cited WMDP-style hazardous-capability batteries in its Sept 2025 DeepSeek and Dec 2025 Kimi K2 evaluations. v2 runs the v1-style MCQ perturbation matrix on a benchmark whose outputs feed regulatory decisions.
4. **The judge layer is where the multi-judge story lives.** Open-weights judge pool of Qwen 2.5-72B-Instruct, DeepSeek V4 Pro, Llama 3.3-70B-Instruct, and optionally Mistral Large 2411 lets us decompose ranking variance into model, judge-identity, judge-family, prompt template, and interactions via standard generalizability-theory machinery (Cronbach, Gleser, Nanda, Rajaratnam 1972).
5. **Quantization is a first-class perturbation axis, not a deployment detail.** The vLLM team (Kübler, Kurtić et al., AWS × Red Hat AI, "The State of FP8 KV-Cache and Attention Quantization in vLLM," vllm.ai/blog/2026-04-22-fp8-kvcache) documented that on Hopper "FP8 accuracy dropped from 91% (BF16 baseline) to just 13% — a regression traced to imprecise FP32 accumulation in the Tensor Cores," with their two-level accumulation fix restoring it to 89%. Document quantization explicitly per run card.

