## Details

### 1. Cross-Cutting Methodology

#### 1.A Perturbation Design Philosophy

Cite, in priority:

- Saltelli, A., Annoni, P., Azzini, I., Campolongo, F., Ratto, M., Tarantola, S. (2010). "Variance based sensitivity analysis of model output. Design and estimator for the total sensitivity index." *Computer Physics Communications* 181(2):259–270. The radial design and the canonical $S_i / S_{T_i}$ estimators.
- Saltelli, A., Ratto, M., Andres, T., Campolongo, F., Cariboni, J., Gatelli, D., Saisana, M., Tarantola, S. (2008). *Global Sensitivity Analysis: The Primer.* Wiley. Textbook.
- Sobol', I. M. (2001). "Global sensitivity indices for nonlinear mathematical models and their Monte Carlo estimates." *Mathematics and Computers in Simulation* 55(1–3):271–280. Foundational decomposition.
- Borgonovo, E. (2007). "A new uncertainty importance measure." *Reliability Engineering & System Safety* 92(6):771–784. Moment-independent δ; use when output distribution is bounded/bimodal (true for MCQ accuracy).
- Plischke, E., Borgonovo, E., Smith, C. L. (2013). "Global sensitivity measures from given data." *European Journal of Operational Research* 226(3):536–550. Estimators from existing samples.
- Pianosi, F., Beven, K., Freer, J., Hall, J. W., Rougier, J., Stephenson, D. B., Wagener, T. (2016). "Sensitivity analysis of environmental models: A systematic review with practical workflow." *Environmental Modelling & Software* 79:214–232. The recommended high-level recipe.

**Design choice by regime.**

| Design | When | Cost (k factors, N base) |
|---|---|---|
| Full factorial | k ≤ 5, levels ≤ 3, want every interaction | $\prod_i L_i$ |
| Partial-cross block (v1 design) | Exploration, main effects + light interaction sampling | depends on block structure |
| Latin hypercube | Continuous screening before Sobol' | $N \approx 10k$ |
| Saltelli radial / Sobol' | Variance decomposition with $S_i, S_{T_i}$ | $N(k+2)$ |
| Morris elementary effects | Cheap screening to identify inactive factors | $N_R(k+1), N_R \in [10,100]$ |

**Saltelli sample size.** Per Zhang, X.-Y., Trame, M., Lesko, L. J., Schmidt, S. (2015), "Sobol Sensitivity Analysis: A Tool to Guide the Development and Evaluation of Systems Pharmacology Models" (PMC5006244), reliable Sobol' indices require N in $[10^2, 10^4]$. With k≈6 axes target $N=1024$ → total $N(k+2)=8192$ runs per benchmark per model. Report bootstrap 95% CIs on $S_i$ and $S_{T_i}$; if dominant-factor CI exceeds 10% of estimate, double N.

**v2 candidate axes** (per-benchmark specialisation in §2–§6):

- A1 prompt template (4–6 levels)
- A2 system prompt (3–5 levels)
- A3 few-shot count (0/1/3/5)
- A4 choice ordering (2: original / seed-pinned shuffled)
- A5 decoding (3: greedy / T=0.7 top_p=0.95 / T=1.0 top_p=1.0)
- A6 quantization (2–3 levels — bf16 / fp8 / awq-int4)

Reference for the prompt-sensitivity literature this matrix targets: Sclar, M., Choi, Y., Tsvetkov, Y., Suhr, A. (2024) ICLR; Mizrahi, M. et al. (2024) TACL multi-prompt evaluation; Zhuo, J., Zhang, S., Fang, X., Duan, H. et al. (2024) "ProSA: Assessing and Understanding the Prompt Sensitivity of LLMs," Findings of EMNLP 2024; Polo et al. 2024 on efficient LLM evaluation.

#### 1.B Variance Decomposition Methodology

Two distinct tools, used in different parts of the matrix.

**Generalizability theory (G-theory)** — for judge-graded benchmarks.

- Cronbach, L. J., Gleser, G. C., Nanda, H., Rajaratnam, N. (1972). *The Dependability of Behavioral Measurements: Theory of Generalizability for Scores and Profiles.* Wiley. Foundational.
- Brennan, R. L. (2001). *Generalizability Theory.* Springer. Modern reference; variance-component estimators (ANOVA, REML, MIVQUE).
- Shavelson, R. J., Webb, N. M., Rowley, G. L. (1989). "Generalizability theory." *American Psychologist* 44(6):922–932. Tutorial.

G-study facets for v2 multi-judge analysis: object of measurement $p$ = model response; facets $i$ = item, $r$ = judge, $t$ = prompt template. Crossed $p \times i \times r \times t$ where possible, nested otherwise. Report $\sigma^2_p, \sigma^2_i, \sigma^2_r, \sigma^2_t$, two-ways, residual. D-study: generalisability coefficient $E\rho^2$ (relative) and Φ (absolute) under varying judge/item/prompt counts. Use REML point estimates with BCa bootstrap 95% CIs (1000 resamples). Set negative variance estimates to 0 with the bias-acknowledgement convention (Brennan 2001 §3).

**Sobol' / Shapley sensitivity** — for non-judge benchmarks and the perturbation matrix proper. Report $S_i, S_{T_i}$ with CIs; sum-to-one diagnostic; large $S_{T_i}-S_i$ means strong interactions.

**Hybrid benchmarks** (agentic with both scaffold and judge): G-theory for the judge facet, Sobol' for the scaffold/wrapper.

**Hierarchical-Bayesian companion analysis.** Luettgau, L., Coppock, H., Dubois, M., Summerfield, C., Ududec, C. (2025). "HiBayES: A Hierarchical Bayesian Modeling Framework for AI Evaluation Statistics." arXiv:2505.05602. UK AI Security Institute. Repo: https://github.com/UKGovernmentBEIS/hibayes. Per the abstract: "we introduce HiBayES, a generalizable Hierarchical Bayesian modeling framework for AI Evaluation Statistics. HiBayES supports robust inferences in classical question-answer benchmarks and advanced agentic evaluations, particularly in low-data scenarios (e.g., < 20 data points per evaluation). Built on Generalized Linear Models (GLMs), Bayesian data analysis, and formal model comparison, HiBayES provides principled uncertainty quantification and robust parameter estimation." Use HiBayES as a secondary analysis on cross-benchmark, cross-model aggregates; the frequentist G-theory + Sobol' results are primary, HiBayES provides the publish-well uncertainty version.

#### 1.C Sequential and Anytime-Valid Testing

- Howard, S. R., Ramdas, A., McAuliffe, J., Sekhon, J. (2021). "Time-uniform, nonparametric, nonasymptotic confidence sequences." *Annals of Statistics* 49(2):1055–1080. DOI:10.1214/20-AOS1991. arXiv:1810.08240.
- Ramdas, A., Grünwald, P., Vovk, V., Wang, R. (2023). "Game-theoretic statistics and safe anytime-valid inference." *Statistical Science* 38(4):576–601. The e-process umbrella.
- Waudby-Smith, I., Ramdas, A. (2024). "Estimating means of bounded random variables by betting." *Journal of the Royal Statistical Society B* 86(1):1–27. The right tool for $[0,1]$-bounded scores — exactly our regime for accuracy and refusal-rate cells.
- Howard, S. R., Waudby-Smith, I., Ramdas, A. (2019–). `confseq`: software for confidence sequences and uniform boundaries. https://github.com/gostevehoward/confseq. Use this library; do not implement uniform boundaries from scratch.

**Recommended default.** Use the betting-based confidence sequence for every cell where the score is a bounded mean. Stop a cell when the CS half-width is below a pre-registered threshold (0.02). Every stopping decision is logged in the run card. Do not use fixed-sample $z$-tests with peek-then-stop policies; that is p-hacking and inflates Type I error.

#### 1.D Judge Analysis Methodology

**Preference Leakage Score (PLS).**

- Li, D., Sun, R., Huang, Y., Zhong, M., Jiang, B., Han, J., Zhang, X., Wang, W., Liu, H. (2025). "Preference Leakage: A Contamination Problem in LLM-as-a-Judge." arXiv:2502.01534 (v1 Feb 3 2025; v3 Mar 4 2026). Repository: https://github.com/David-Li0406/Preference-Leakage. From the paper: "Through extensive experiments, we empirically confirm the bias of judges towards their related student models caused by preference leakage across multiple LLM baselines and benchmarks."

PLS quantifies how much a judge favours student models related to it across three relatedness classes (same model, inheritance, same family). Mojave's `preference_leakage.rs` implements Li et al. eq. 5–6; deploy as: for each (judge $J$, candidate pair $M_1, M_2$) compute pairwise preferences across items, compute the relatedness vector between $J$ and each $M_i$, then the per-pair PLS. Stratify model ranking by judge-family and report any cross-family inversion.

**Open-weights judge pool** (rationale: 2 family-related + 2 cross-family neutral).

| Judge | HF repo | Role |
|---|---|---|
| Qwen 2.5-72B-Instruct | `Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct` | family-related to Qwen candidates |
| DeepSeek V4 Pro | `deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-V4-Pro` | family-related to DeepSeek candidate |
| Llama 3.3-70B-Instruct | `meta-llama/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct` | cross-family neutral |
| Mistral Large 2411 (optional) | `mistralai/Mistral-Large-Instruct-2411` | second cross-family neutral |

Each pair scored in both orders, averaged, per Zheng et al. (2023) position-bias control.

**Inter-rater reliability.**

- Gwet, K. L. (2014). *Handbook of Inter-Rater Reliability*, 4th ed. Advanced Analytics. Gwet's AC1 (nominal) and AC2 (ordinal with weights). AC2 is more robust than Krippendorff's α under high marginal prevalence (the "kappa paradox").
- Krippendorff, K. (2018). *Content Analysis: An Introduction to Its Methodology*, 4th ed. SAGE.
- Fleiss, J. L. (1971). "Measuring nominal scale agreement among many raters." *Psychological Bulletin* 76(5):378–382. Multi-rater nominal.
- Cohen, J. (1960). "A coefficient of agreement for nominal scales." *Educational and Psychological Measurement* 20(1):37–46. Two-rater nominal.

Default: Gwet's AC2 with linear weights as the primary statistic; Krippendorff's α as robustness check. Both with 95% BCa bootstrap CIs (Gwet 2014 ch. 5). Sirbu et al. (Cronos Clinical Consulting / ISCTM 19th Annual Poster, 2023) document AC2 having higher ROC sensitivity and threshold values than α and Cohen's κ on ordinal clinical-trial ratings, validating the choice for ordinal judge scores.

**Calibration before treating judge outputs as data.** Run a 100-item gold set (MT-Bench/Arena-Hard human preferences when available; AgentHarm rubric labels; TruthfulQA original human evaluations). Compute per-judge accuracy, Cohen's κ vs gold, position-bias rate, verbosity-bias rate. If gold-κ < 0.4 (Landis-Koch "fair" threshold), exclude judge and document.

Reference for biases: Zheng, L., Chiang, W.-L., Sheng, Y., Zhuang, S., Wu, Z., Zhuang, Y., Lin, Z., Li, Z., Li, D., Xing, E. P., Zhang, H., Gonzalez, J. E., Stoica, I. (2023). "Judging LLM-as-a-Judge with MT-Bench and Chatbot Arena." NeurIPS 2023 D&B Track. arXiv:2306.05685. Position, verbosity, and self-enhancement biases identified and partially mitigated.

**AISI Skewed Score companion.** Dubois, M., Coppock, H., Giulianelli, M., Flesch, T., Luettgau, L., Ududec, C. (2025). "Skewed Score: A statistical framework to assess autograders." arXiv:2507.03772. AISI blog (Jul 9 2025): "Our new framework can assess the reliability of LLM evaluators, while simultaneously answering a primary research question." Bayesian GLMs (ordered logistic for finite-range scores; Bradley–Terry-style for preferences) jointly modelling grader effects, item effects, and inter-rater agreement.

#### 1.E Inspect Framework Integration

**Pinned versions** (PyPI, as of May 20–24 2026):

- `inspect-ai==0.3.224` (May 20 2026). MIT, Python ≥3.10. Prior pins 0.3.223 (May 18), 0.3.222 (May 16), 0.3.220 (May 8).
- `inspect-evals==0.5.2` (Mar 19 2026). GitHub `UKGovernmentBEIS/inspect_evals`. Registry transition announced May 8 2026.
- `inspect-scout==0.4.28` (Meridian Labs, MIT). For transcript-level analysis.

**Core abstractions.** `Task` (dataset + solver + scorer), `Dataset`, `Solver` (chain), `Scorer` (rule-based or model-graded), `Sandbox` (Docker / k8s / Proxmox).

**EvalLog format.** `.eval` binary format default since v0.3.46; samples have globally unique `uuid` fields since the v0.3.70-era CHANGELOG entry: "Eval log: Add option to select sample by uuid in read_eval_log_sample()." Use `read_eval_log_sample(log_file, uuid=...)` to retrieve a single sample for spot-check verification against a sealed run card. Log directory manifest via `write_log_dir_manifest()`. `samples_df()`, `evals_df()`, `messages_df()`, `events_df()` for dataframe extraction.

**Driving perturbations without forking.**

1. Prompt template / system prompt: wrap the upstream solver in a Mojave-side solver that mutates `TaskState.messages` before the model call.
2. Few-shot count, choice ordering: pass via `task_args`. If task does not expose the parameter, write a thin local task that imports the upstream dataset/scorer.
3. Sandboxing: `--sandbox docker` with Epoch AI ghcr.io pre-built images for SWE-Bench; authenticate via `gh auth token | docker login ghcr.io -u USERNAME --password-stdin`.
4. Determinism: `--seed`, pin model revision (HF SHA), log all `GenerateConfig` fields.

**Eval-set parallelism.** `inspect eval-set` is the preferred entry point for multi-task runs; tracks completed work in `log-dir` and retries up to 10 by default. Every retry is a new run card chained into the audit log.

#### 1.F vLLM + Open-Weights Inference Recipes

**Pinned**: `vllm==0.21.0` (May 15 2026, Apache-2.0, Python ≥3.10 <3.15, CUDA 13.0 default wheel). Supports FP8, MXFP8/MXFP4, NVFP4, INT8/INT4, GPTQ, AWQ, GGUF, compressed-tensors, ModelOpt.

**Qwen 2.5-7B-Instruct** (continuity with v1):
```
vllm serve Qwen/Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct \
  --tensor-parallel-size 1 --max-model-len 32768 \
  --dtype bfloat16 --gpu-memory-utilization 0.9 --seed 42
```
Fits on a single A100/H100-80GB or on 2× RTX 3090-24GB with TP=2.

**Qwen 2.5-72B-Instruct**. Per the official Qwen vLLM deployment guide (`qwen.readthedocs.io/en/v2.5/deployment/vllm.html`): `vllm serve Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct --tensor-parallel-size 4`. For long contexts (>32768 tokens) add YaRN `rope_scaling` to config.json only when needed. Quantization caveat: Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct intermediate size is 29568; $29568/(128\times8) = 28.875$, so self-quantized GPTQ with `group_size=128` only supports `tensor_parallel_size=1` or 2 without weight padding. AWQ with `q_group_size=64` likewise; for TP=4 AWQ use `q_group_size=32`. Source: Qwen quantization docs and HF discussion `Benasd/Qwen2.5-VL-72B-Instruct-AWQ/discussions/2`.

**DeepSeek V4 Pro**. Native FP4+FP8 Instruct checkpoints (per DeepSeek-style architecture and third-party deployment guides circulating in 2026). Total footprint ≈ 170–175 GB (158 GB weights + ~10 GB KV cache at 1M context + runtime). Fits on 2× H200-141GB or 4× A100-80GB:
```
vllm serve deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-V4-Pro \
  --trust-remote-code --tensor-parallel-size 4 \
  --enable-expert-parallel --max-model-len 65536 --seed 42
```
vLLM 0.21.0 supports DeepSeek-V3 in FP8/BF16 per `docs.vllm.ai/projects/recipes/en/latest/DeepSeek/DeepSeek-V3.html`. Verify the V4 recipe at run time; fall back to V3 patterns if not yet published. **Do not** stack INT4 quantization on already-quantized FP4+FP8 V4 checkpoints — quality degrades on math/reasoning/agentic tasks.

**Quantization as a perturbation axis.** Kübler, P., Kurtić, E. et al. (AWS × Red Hat AI). "The State of FP8 KV-Cache and Attention Quantization in vLLM." vLLM Blog, Apr 22 2026 (vllm.ai/blog/2026-04-22-fp8-kvcache). Verbatim: "FP8 accuracy dropped from 91% (BF16 baseline) to just 13% — a regression traced to imprecise FP32 accumulation in the Tensor Cores"; the two-level accumulation fix restored 89% on the 128k needle-in-a-haystack task. Confirmed in summary by @vllm_project on X: "two-level accumulation in FA3 takes 128k needle-in-a-haystack from 13% → 89%." Treat quantization as a first-class factor.

**Determinism.** vLLM is not bitwise-deterministic across batch sizes or GPU types. Pin GPU type, batch size, vLLM version. Greedy decoding is reproducible token-by-token only within a fixed (GPU, batch-size, vLLM-version) tuple.

#### 1.G Statistical Reporting Standards

- Wilson, E. B. (1927). "Probable inference, the law of succession, and statistical inference." *JASA* 22(158):209–212. Wilson score interval for proportions — default for accuracy and refusal-rate CIs.
- Efron, B., Tibshirani, R. J. (1993). *An Introduction to the Bootstrap.* Chapman & Hall. BCa intervals for variance components, Sobol' indices, Gwet's AC2.
- Cohen, J. (1988). *Statistical Power Analysis for the Behavioral Sciences*, 2nd ed. Erlbaum. Report Cohen's $d$ (means) and $h$ (proportions) alongside any p-value.
- Pineau, J., Vincent-Lamarre, P., Sinha, K., Larivière, V., Beygelzimer, A., d'Alché-Buc, F., Fox, E., Larochelle, H. (2020). "Improving reproducibility in machine learning research (a report from the NeurIPS 2019 reproducibility program)." arXiv:2003.12206. Conform to the NeurIPS reproducibility checklist.

Defaults: Wilson 95% CIs for accuracies; BCa bootstrap 95% CIs (1000 resamples) for all non-standard statistics; effect-size + CI for comparisons; per-judge AND judge-averaged reporting, never a silent average.

