### 2. SWE-Bench Verified

#### Scientific background and citations

- Jimenez, C., Yang, J., Wettig, A., Yao, S., Pei, K., Press, O., Narasimhan, K. (2024). "SWE-bench: Can Language Models Resolve Real-World GitHub Issues?" *ICLR 2024.* arXiv:2310.06770. 2294 instances across 12 Python repositories.
- OpenAI Preparedness team (Aug 13, 2024). "Introducing SWE-bench Verified." OpenAI blog (openai.com/index/introducing-swe-bench-verified/). The human-validated 500-instance subset. Per swebench.com: "SWE-bench Verified is a human-filtered subset of 500 instances from SWE-bench, created in collaboration with OpenAI. Human annotators reviewed each instance to ensure the problem descriptions are clear, the test patches are correct, and the tasks are solvable given the available information."
- Repository: https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench. Verified subset HF dataset: `princeton-nlp/SWE-bench_Verified`. Retrieval variants: `_oracle`, `_bm25_13K/27K/40K`.

#### Methodological angle for v2: agentic-harness variance

Documented integrator findings (verify each at write-up; cite the source that originally published the number).

- Morph LLC (2026), "SWE-Bench Explained: Benchmarks, Verified, Pro, and the 2026 Leaderboard" (morphllm.com/swe-benchmark): "The same model (Opus 4.5) scores 45.9% with standardized scaffolding and 51.8% with Auggie's scaffolding." This is the headline number for "scaffold > model" framing. Augment Code's own blog (augmentcode.com/blog/auggie-tops-swe-bench-pro) corroborates: "Auggie CLI takes the top spot on SWE-bench Pro, solving 51.80% of real-world software engineering tasks. For reference, Scale's own leaderboard shows Claude Opus 4.5 hitting 45.89% when run through SWE-Agent."
- Particula.tech (2026), "Claude Opus 4.6 vs GPT-5.3 vs Gemini 3.1: Best for Code 2026" (particula.tech/blog/claude-opus-vs-gpt5-codex-vs-gemini-2026): "SWE-bench Pro shows a 22-point performance swing from scaffold changes alone. The model is your ceiling, but the harness determines how close you get to it."
